'''Johann Anton Leisewitz''' (born 9 May 1752 in [[Hanover]], died 10 September 1806 in [[Braunschweig]]) was a [[Germany|German]] lawyer and dramatic [[poet]], and a central figure of the [[Sturm und Drang]] era. He is best known for his play ''[[Julius of Tarent]]'' (1776), that inspired [[Friedrich Schiller]] and is considered the forerunner of Schiller's quintessential Sturm und Drang work ''[[The Robbers]]'' (1781).<ref>[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/335498/Johann-Anton-Leisewitz?anchor=ref141414 Johann Anton Leisewitz], ''[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]''</ref>

==Biography==
He went to [[University of Göttingen|Göttingen]] in 1770, and became a member of the circle of poets called [[Göttinger Hainbund|Der Hainbund]], which included [[Friedrich Leopold zu Stolberg-Stolberg|Stolberg]] and [[Johann Heinrich Voss|Voss]], and contributed two poems to the ''[[Göttinger Musenalmanach]]'' for 1775, both essentially dramatic and democratic in tone. In 1775, at [[Braunschweig|Brunswick]], and later at [[Berlin]] and [[Weimar]], he met and soon counted among his friends [[Johann Joachim Eschenburg|Eschenburg]], [[Moses Mendelssohn]], [[Gotthold Ephraim Lessing|Lessing]], [[Friedrich Nicolai|Nicolai]], [[Johann Gottfried von Herder|Herder]], and [[Johann Wolfgang von Goethe|Goethe]]. His single complete play, ''[[Julius of Tarent]]'' (1776), was written in Lessing's style and with much of the latter's dramatic technique. The play was a favorite of [[Friedrich Schiller]], and was frequently acted in Germany. It also inspired [[Friedrich Maximilian Klinger]], who was employed as playwright by Leisewitz' father-in-law [[Abel Seyler]].

==Personal life==
[[File:Sophie Leisewitz née Seyler.jpg|thumb|His wife Sophie Seyler]]

He married ''Sophie'' Marie Katharina [[Seyler family|Seyler]] (1762–1833) in Hamburg in 1781. She was the daughter of famed Swiss-born theatre director [[Abel Seyler]] and stepdaughter of actress [[Friederike Sophie Seyler]], and grew up with her uncle [[J.G.R. Andreae]] in Hanover. Her brother was banker [[Ludwig Erdwin Seyler]], who became by marriage a member of the [[Berenberg-Gossler-Seyler banking dynasty|Berenberg-Gossler banking dynasty]].<ref>[http://www.deutsche-biographie.de/sfz50045.html Leisewitz, Johann Anton], ''[[Neue Deutsche Biographie]]''</ref> Leisewitz was a distant relative of his wife on the Andreae side, and had been a frequent visitor in the Andreae home, with its large library, in his youth. He would later refer to J.G.R. Andreae as his uncle.<ref>Paul Warren Noble, ''The life and works of Johann Anton Leisewitz'', University of Wisconsin-Madison, 1976, p. 107</ref> His diaries and his letters to his wife have been published.<ref>Johann Anton Leisewitzen: ''Briefe an seine Braut'', Gesellschaft der Bibliophilen, 1906</ref> The letters sent between Johann Anton Leisewitz and Sophie Seyler have been described as some of the most beautiful love letters of the late 18th century.<ref>Paul Herrmann, ''Liebesbekenntnisse berühmter deutscher Männer und Frauen; 100 bewegende Briefe von Luther bis Rilke'', p. 90, M. Pawlak Verlagsgesellschaft, 1985, {{ISBN|3881992391}}</ref>

