{{Infobox book | <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> | name = The Copernican Revolution: Planetary Astronomy in the Development of Western Thought | image = File:The Copernican Revolution, 1957 edition.gif | caption = Cover of the first edition | author = [[Thomas Kuhn|Thomas S. Kuhn]] | country = United States | language = English | subject = [[History of astronomy]] | publisher = [[Harvard University Press]] | pub_date = 1957 | media_type = Print ([[Hardcover]] and [[Paperback]]) | pages = 297 | isbn = 0-674-17103-9 }} '''''The Copernican Revolution''''' is a 1957 book by the philosopher [[Thomas Kuhn]], in which the author provides an analysis of the [[Copernican Revolution]], documenting the pre-Ptolemaic understanding through the [[Ptolemaic system]] and its variants until the eventual acceptance of the [[Kepler's laws of planetary motion|Keplerian system]].<ref name=Kuhn>{{cite book |last = Kuhn |first = Thomas |authorlink = Thomas Kuhn |title = The Copernican Revolution |publisher = [[Harvard University Press]] |date = 1957 |type = Copyright renewed 1985 |isbn = 0-674-17103-9}} </ref>
Kuhn argues that the Ptolemaic system provided broader appeal than a simple astronomical system but also became intertwined in broader philosophical and theological beliefs. Kuhn argues that this broader appeal made it more difficult for other systems to be proposed.<ref name=butter> {{cite journal | last = Butterfield | first = Herbert | authorlink = Herbert Butterfield | title = The Copernican Revolution: Planetary Astronomy in the Development of Western Thought by Thomas S. Kuhn | journal = [[The American Historical Review]] | volume = 63 | issue = 3 | pages = 656–657 | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | location = UK | date =April 1958 | jstor =1848896 | doi =10.1086/ahr/63.3.656 }} Text available on [[JSTOR]]</ref><ref name=Hall> {{cite journal |doi=10.1093/bjps/21.2.196 |url=http://bjps.oxfordjournals.org/content/21/2/196.full.pdf+html?sid=8a197794-d280-4474-a250-ab49b8138768 |format=article available on web page | last = Hall | first = Richard J. | title = Kuhn and the Copernican Revolution | journal =[[The British Journal for the Philosophy of Science]] | volume = 21 | issue = 2 | pages = 196–197 | publisher = [[Oxford University Press]] | date = May 1970 | jstor =686700}}</ref><ref> {{cite journal |last = Swerdlow |first = N. M. |title = An Essay on Thomas Kuhn's First Scientific Revolution, The Copernican Revolution |journal = [[Proceedings of the American Philosophical Society]] |volume = 148 |issue = 1 |pages = 64–120 |publisher = [[American Philosophical Society]] |location = Philadelphia, PA |date = March 2004 |url = http://www.amphilsoc.org/sites/default/files/480106.pdf |jstor = 1558245 |accessdate = 2014-02-20 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20110612172417/http://www.amphilsoc.org/sites/default/files/480106.pdf |archivedate = 2011-06-12 |df = }}</ref><ref name=westman>Westman, Robert S. "Two Cultures or One?: A Second Look at Kuhn's The Copernican Revolution." Isis (1994): 79-115.</ref>
==Summation== Kuhn summarized at the end of ''The Copernican Revolution'', citing the permanent achievements of Copernicus and Newton, while comparing the incommensurability of Newtonian physics with Aristotelian concepts that preceded the then new physics. Kuhn also noted that discoveries, such as that produced by Newton, were not in agreement with the prevailing world view during his lifetime.<ref name=westman/>
